<div class="row">
    <div class="col-8">
        <h3>Overview</h3>
        <br />
        <div class="ptext">
            <p>
                Earlier we discussed the Module pattern in jQuery, which, as you know, is JavaScript's manifestation of the Singleton pattern.  The jQuery code base lives in a single Module which executes only once.  Here are the relevant lines:
            </p>
<pre class="prettyprint">
(function (window, undefined) {

  // ~ 10,000 lines of code ...

})( window );
</pre>
            <p>
                This ensures that a web page will have at most one instance of jQuery (or its alias $).
                As an aside, you can have multiple versions of jQuery running on a page with the help of the <span class="cd">jQuery.noConflict()</span> method.
            </p>


        </div>
